This paper is likely to belong to the category of cs.LG (Machine Learning) as it proposes a new loss function for deep domain adaptation models. It also involves training a neural network to learn domain-invariant feature space, which is a common technique in machine learning. 

The paper also deals with computer vision tasks, such as image classification, which suggests that it could belong to cs.CV (Computer Vision) as well. 

Additionally, the paper involves learning discriminative representations, which is a common problem in artificial intelligence, suggesting that it could belong to cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). 

The paper also involves natural language processing tasks, such as sentiment analysis, which suggests that it could belong to cs.CL (Computation and Language). 

Finally, the paper involves experiments on benchmark datasets, which suggests that it could belong to cs.MM (Multimedia).
